						<br>
						</td>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 1160px;">
						<ul class="normalList">
					
                        <li>Brand and Generic: searches both brand and generic drug names. This is the default search method.
                            </li>
                        <br />
                        <li>Brand: searches brand drug names.</li>
						<br />
                        <li>Generic: searches generic drug names.</li>
						<br />
                        <li>Therapeutic Class: searches for therapeutic class as assigned by the manufacturer. Therapeutic classes are included in monograph headers</li>
                        <br/>
                        <li>Manufacturer: searches drug manufacturers.</li>
                        <br/>
						<li>DIN: searches Drug Identification Numbers (DIN). </li>
                        <br/>
                       
                        
						
                    </ul>
                    <br />
						</td>
						</table>
						
                    
                    <p>2. Click in the<strong> Enter full or partial text:</strong> text box and type the term you want to search for.</p>
                   
                    <table style="text-align: left; width: 100%;" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2">
						
						<tr>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 9px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
						<br>
						</td>
						<tr>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 4px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 1156px;"><b><font color="green">Tip</font></b>: after you type a second character in the text box, an autocomplete drop-down list appears that contains options that match the characters you have typed. You can select from the list or keep typing to narrow your selection. If you select an item from the autocomplete drop-down list, the search function activates on that item automatically.</p>
						
						</td>
						
						<tr>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 9px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
					
						</td>
						
						<tr>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 4px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
						<td style="vertical-align: top; width: 1156px;"><b><font color="green">Tip</font></b>: When searching for a drug, you can add an asterisk at the beginning of the characters you type to include autocomplete options and search results that contain those typed characters at the beginning, end, or nested within drug names. For example, typing "*aro" returns all drug names (brand and generic) that begin or end with "aro" or contain "aro" nested within the drug name. The asterisk is implied at the end of your typed text so there is no need to include it there.</p><br/><br/>
                 		
						</td>
						
                    </table>
					
                 
					
					<p>3. Click <b>Search.</b></p>
					
